<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1118,2007]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1442,1467]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Remarks.</emphasis>
The material examined here entirely coincides with the re-description of the type-series of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hickson &amp; Gravely" authorityYear="1907" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tubulariidae" genus="Hydractinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="dendritica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">H. dendritica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pena Cantero, A. L." box="[421,660,1478,1503]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="369 - 392" refId="ref44411" refString="Pena Cantero, A. L. (2015) Review of some little-known benthic hydroids (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa) from the Southern Ocean. Zootaxa, 3972 (3), 369 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3972.3.4" type="journal article" year="2015">Peña Cantero (2015)</bibRefCitation>
, including the presence of erect stems, dwarf gonophores (
<figureCitation box="[1339,1421,1478,1503]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1414,1436]" captionTargetBox="[161,1423,205,1385]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[150,1436,195,1393]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. a–f Hydractinia dendritica: a–b general view of the colony; c detail of spines; d gastrozooids and dactylozooid (arrow); e gonozooid with gonophores; f dactylozooid (arrow). g Eudendrium antarcticum: female gonophore. h Eudendrium generale: female gonophore. i, k Eudendrium scotti: i gonozooid with male gonophores; k colony. j Eudendrium sp.2: gonozooid with male gonophores." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608533/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 3e</figureCitation>
), and dactylozooids (
<figureCitation box="[374,455,1514,1539]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1414,1436]" captionTargetBox="[161,1423,205,1385]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[150,1436,195,1393]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. a–f Hydractinia dendritica: a–b general view of the colony; c detail of spines; d gastrozooids and dactylozooid (arrow); e gonozooid with gonophores; f dactylozooid (arrow). g Eudendrium antarcticum: female gonophore. h Eudendrium generale: female gonophore. i, k Eudendrium scotti: i gonozooid with male gonophores; k colony. j Eudendrium sp.2: gonozooid with male gonophores." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608533/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 3f</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hickson &amp; Gravely" authorityYear="1907" box="[477,736,1514,1539]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tubulariidae" genus="Hydractinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="dendritica">
<emphasis box="[477,736,1514,1539]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydractinia dendritica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to have different growing strategies depending on the substrate on which it develops, as it has already been reported for other congeneric (
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert, P." box="[1147,1345,1550,1575]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="221 - 302" refId="ref46596" refString="Schuchert, P. (2008 a) The European athecate hydroids and their medusae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria): Filifera part 3. Revue Suisse De Zoologie, 115, 221 - 302. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 80426" type="journal article" year="2008">Schuchert 2008a</bibRefCitation>
). In the material examined, some sections of the same colony (or whole colonies) develop sharp spines when gastrozooids and dactyolozooids are not yet developed or are proportionally less abundant (
<figureCitation box="[1056,1139,1622,1647]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1414,1436]" captionTargetBox="[161,1423,205,1385]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[150,1436,195,1393]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. a–f Hydractinia dendritica: a–b general view of the colony; c detail of spines; d gastrozooids and dactylozooid (arrow); e gonozooid with gonophores; f dactylozooid (arrow). g Eudendrium antarcticum: female gonophore. h Eudendrium generale: female gonophore. i, k Eudendrium scotti: i gonozooid with male gonophores; k colony. j Eudendrium sp.2: gonozooid with male gonophores." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608533/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 3c</figureCitation>
), while other portions (or colonies) are almost deprived of spines but have abundant gastrozooids, and some dactylozooids (c. one dactylozooid per 10–20 gastrozooids). The fully mature colony, where gonozooids carrying gonophores are found, have a sort of perisarcal wall joining spines, as a kind of “room divider”, which could act as an extra-protection for the reproductive polyps (
<figureCitation box="[434,545,1766,1791]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1414,1436]" captionTargetBox="[161,1423,205,1385]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[150,1436,195,1393]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. a–f Hydractinia dendritica: a–b general view of the colony; c detail of spines; d gastrozooids and dactylozooid (arrow); e gonozooid with gonophores; f dactylozooid (arrow). g Eudendrium antarcticum: female gonophore. h Eudendrium generale: female gonophore. i, k Eudendrium scotti: i gonozooid with male gonophores; k colony. j Eudendrium sp.2: gonozooid with male gonophores." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608533/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 3b, e</figureCitation>
). All this different growing morphologies can be observed in the same colony, and we suggest they correspond either to differences in the substrate used or to ontogenetic changes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1118,2007]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,502,1838,1863]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ecology and distribution.</emphasis>
The species had been found once, in McMurdo Sound (Ross Sea), at a depth of 
<quantity metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="m" value="18.0">18 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hickson, S. J. &amp; Gravely, F. H." box="[191,489,1874,1899]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref42832" refString="Hickson, S. J. &amp; Gravely, F. H. (1907) Coelenterata. II. Hydroid zoophytes. National Antarctic Expedition (S. S. Discovery) 1901 - 1904, Natural History, 3, 1 - 34." type="journal article" year="1907">Hickson &amp; Gravely 1907</bibRefCitation>
); our material was collected from several locations in the Weddell Sea, at depths between 62 and 
<quantity box="[341,416,1911,1935]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7299999999999995" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="m" value="473.0">473 m</quantity>
, growing on different substrates (see 
<tableCitation box="[850,924,1910,1935]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="53.[147,224,585,605]" captionText="TABLE 3. Substrate and epibionts of the species inventoried." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Tab. 3</tableCitation>
). Present contribution constitutes the second report of the species, and the first evidence from both the Weddell Sea and West 
<collectingCountry box="[1067,1187,1946,1971]" name="Antarctica" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
, pointing to a circum- Antarctic distribution.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
